<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-02-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-02-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="591" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d591">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.00/879.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 60.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Amercan Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-28">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 28, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to my despatch No. 57 of
                            February 20, 1914, relative to the blockade by the Haitian Government of
                            the various ports in the Republic, including that of Cape Haitien, the
                            second port in importance in Haiti, I have the honor to enclose herewith
                            copy of an unsigned communication<note n="9" xml:id="d591fn9">Not
                                printed.</note> from the Haitian Foreign Office dated February 27,
                            1914, announcing the lifting of the blockade by the Haitian
                            Government.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Madison R. Smith</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>